Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly with Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea has already been put into service.
Must deliver gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the giant Russian gas, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate bufet, at the opening of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline connecting directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and its counterpart in the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have evolved together the wheel of the valve, which controls the entry of Russian gas in the grid of Western Europe.
With this new pipeline, each year will reach 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas to Western Europe via a first took of 1,224 km linking the St Petersburg region with the land of mecklemburgo-pomerania.
A second tube should be completed in late 2012 that will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e., enough to cover the entire French consumption.
Moreover, there is already talk of the possibility of constructing a third tube for the same journey.
For Gazprom, the expeditious completion of this huge labour introduced Aires of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had been firmly opposed to the project.
Indeed, Nord Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding the course for ground third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
